<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>



<section xml:id="lesson5_1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Basic Probability</title>

<p>
In this chapter, we'll first review what probability means - and what it doesn't mean. 
Next, we'll learn how to combine probabilities for independent events. 
Throughout the chapter, we will explore probability using a common context in which you often encounter probabilities - 
weather forecasts. We will then apply it to the quantum context, in which we calculate the 
probability of measuring one, two, or more qubits in a particular state.

</p>

<section xml:id="sec-probability-meaning">
    <title>What a Probability Means</title>
What do weather forecasts really mean?
Look at the exercise below and identify what you can conclude from a weather forecast.
<p>
<image source="L5.1-weather-forecast.png" width="66%" /></p>

 <exercise label="L5-1-Forecast-Events">
      <title>
        Probability in Forecasts
      </title>
      <idx>probability forecast</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Which of the following statements is true based on the weather forecast?</p>
        
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>It is not going to rain at 11pm.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>It is very unlikely to rain at 11pm, but it still might rain.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>It is going to rain at 4am.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>It might rain at 4a, but it might not rain.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice  correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>It is more likely to rain in the morning than in the evening.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Yes! However, there is still a possibility that it rains in the evening and not the morning.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>

      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Think carefully about what a forecast probability means.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>


<p>
What it really means is that if we experienced 100,000 days with these identical conditions,
approximately 40,000 of them would have rain at 4am. However, it does not make a definitive
statement about what is going to happen today.
</p>



<sidebyside widths="50% 50%" valign="top">
   <p>
Probability is not:
<ul><li>Knowledge about the outcome of any individual event</li>
<li>Confirmed or refuted through a single experiment</li>
</ul>
</p>
  <p>
Probability is:
<ul><li>A prediction of the frequency of an outcome of many, many actions
</li>
<li>Confirmed or refuted through many, many experiments</li>
</ul>
</p>
  </sidebyside>
</section>
<section xml:id="sec-independent-probabilities">
    <title>Combining Independent Probabilities</title>
<p> Now that we understand what a probability means, we can learn how to combine probabilities for independent events.
Two events are independent if the outcome of one event does not affect the outcome of the other event. 
For example, the outcome of a coin flip is independent of the outcome of another coin flip.</p>

<p> Let's say we have two coins, and we flip both of them at the same time. 
What is the probability that the first coin will be heads?
What is the probability that the second coin will be heads?</p>

<p> Hopefully, in your head, you are calculating the probability of each coin being heads as 50%.
We want to take that result and calculate the probability of both coins being heads at the same time.</p>
<p><image source="L5.1.onecoin.png" width="40%" /></p>
<p> One way to reason about it is to list out all the possible outcomes of flipping two coins.
Because each option is equally likely, the probability of each case is 25%. That means that the probability
of both coins being heads is 25%. Likewise, the probability of both coins being tails is 25%.</p>
<p> You might notice, though,
that two of the choices look the same. That is, two choices have one heads and one tails. 
So the probability that "one coin is heads and the other coin is tails" is 50%, whereas the probability the 
"first coin is heads and the second coin is tails" is 25%.</p>

<p><image source="L5.1.twocoins.png" width="66%" /></p>

<p> This example was fairly simple because we had equal probabilities for each outcome. Let's go to our
weather example and look at how to calculate independent probabilities when the probabilities are not equal.</p>

<p> Let's imagine that I am always running late in the morning, I'm groggy, and I'm just a little spacey, so I don't have a  the 
forecast. It turns out that a particular day has a 50% chance of raining. On any given day, I have a 25% chance of deciding to 
bring a raincoat, just in case. So I have the following scenario:</p> 

<p><image source="L5.n-probs1.png" width="66%" /></p>

<p> Notice that I drew the pictures based on the ratios - 3/4 chance of not bringing a raincoat, and 1/4 chance of bringing a raincoat 
resulted in three shirts and one raincoat. This is similar to how we have been depicting superposition probabilities with our 
visual representation. We can use this to depict all of the possibilities, still repeating possibilities to indicate that they are more likely.
I'll show the process in two steps.</p>

<p><image source="L5.n-probs2.png" width="66%" /></p>
<p><image source="L5.n-probs3.png" width="66%" /></p>

<p> We can see from this final picture that the probabiliti of it being raining AND I forget my rain jacket is 3/8. 
It turns out that we can actually do this with a simple calculation. Given our starting probabilities of .75 forgetting raincoat,
.25 bringing raincoat, and .5 raining, we can calculate the probability of it raining AND forgetting raincoat as .75 * .5 = .375 = 3/8.</p>
<p><image source="L5.n-probsmult.png" width="66%" /></p>

